data.caption:
Informal Reception Given in Commemoration of the Sixtieth Wedding Anniversary of Ogden Pioneers
Quite the most auspicious event of the week in social circles was the informal reception given last evening at the spacious home of Mr. and Mrs. William Driver, 2708 Jefferson avenue where a large number of their host of friends in this city were received and entertained in a splendid manner from eight until 10 o'clock. The Driver home was exceptionally pretty with a wealth of lavendar asters and goldenglow, the flowers being arranged throughout every room in a most artistic manner. Ferns and potted plants vied with the cut flowers in beauty and were also placed most effectively in the parlors and dining room. The affair of last evening celebrated the sixtieth anniversary of the wedding of Mr. and Mrs. Driver, who were married in London, England, August 16, 1858 and who shortly afterward came to this state to help in its upbuilding. Both Mr. and Mrs. Driver have been very active in the growth and advancement of the state and especially the city of Ogden where Mr. Driver conducted his business for many years and assisted in various ways in the upbuilding of the community. Last evening the family of Mr. and Mrs. Driver were present and assisted in receiving the guests and entertaining. The time was pleasantly spent and temptingly prepared refreshments were perfectly served during the entire evening. Mr. and Mrs. Driver were congratulated time and again on their wonderful agility and were extended happy wishes for many more anniversaries.

IN THE MOMENTS MODES
Cinnamon-Color Silver Cloth Suit, Nutria Trimmed
Here is a suit in fashionable color that strikes an original and interesting note in the arrangement of the fur trimming. The season's favorite fur is set in large bias pieces round the skirt of the coat in a way that makes its simple, well-tailored lines striking and different. Another novel note is added by the stitched seams that curve in an unusual cut from the waist to the skirt of the coat. The stitched front of the coat gives a double-breasted effect, through fastening with only two buttons and a narrow belt. The suit is made of the silver cloth in cinnamon color, and the collar and cuffs are of nutria which nearly matches the material. The skirt is one of the very new straight models

INTO ETERNAL REST.
Saturday morning at Lexington a most beautiful and exemplary life was closed when, sweetly as a little child sinking to rest in the arms of its mother, the pure soul of Mrs. Honora Cronin, beloved wife of James Cronin and, mother of the Rev. J. P Cronin, pastor of St. Patrick's church and Vicar General of the diocese, sank peacefully into the sleep that knows no earthly waking to take its flight to the bosom of her Saviour whom she loved and so faithfully served throughout her life. Suffering a fall thirteen months ago and in declining health thereafter, her death was not unexpected. Throughout her illness Mrs. Cronin never complained, but bore her sufferings with a most humble resignation to God's holy will and complete trust in the ever Sacred Heart, in which those of the true faith find comfort and support. She was born in Ireland and on May 6, 1858, was married to James Cronin in Churchtown, County Cork, coming at once to Kentucky and locating at Frankfort in 1859, but for the past forty-five years they have lived at Lexington. To their union were born nine children, of whom four are living, and whose devotion to their mother was beautiful, nursing and caring for her as any mother would her babe. She was truly a model Christian wife and mother and endeared herself to everyone. Last May Mr. and Mrs. Cronin celebrated their golden wedding, having with them their four living children, Rev. James P. and John Cronin, of Louisville, and Michael J. Cronin and Mrs. J. W. Lawrence, of Lexington. The funeral services were held Monday morning at St. Peter's church, Rev. Father Cronin being the celebrant of the solemn requiem high mass. A very touching eulogy telling of the virtues and beautiful qualities characteristic of the departed, was spoken by Rev. Father Punch, the pastor. The remains were laid to rest in the Catholic cemetery. For the bereaved husband and children the Kentucky Irish American feels deepest sympathy.

Allies to Drive Boches Back to Hindenburg Line
Back to the Hindenburg line before snow flies!
That is the immediate program of General Foch and the allied war council.
Allied military observers now believe that the Great Allied Push which will drive the Germans to the Rhine is not contemplated until next spring, when the military strength of America, France and England will reach its zenith.
But in the meantime Gen. Foch will not give over the initiative so successfully adopted in the second battle of the Marne. The allied forces are now strong enough to permit of a continuous offensive pressure against the armies of the Prussian Crown Prince and Prince Rupprecht of Bavaria, and it will be kept up until the Germans are driven to the old Hindenburg line to which they retreated in the spring of 1917.

READ, STOP, THINK
The following extract is from a letter to the present Coroner which appeaaed[sic] in various papers: "In my opinion there is no legal objection to your re-election. (Signed) "M. M. LOGAN, "Attorney General." That is not the question. The question is: CAN THE PRESENT CORONER LEGALLY HOLD TWO OFFICES AT THE SAME TIME--one under the Civil and one under the Federal Government, and draw $5,000 per year from one and $3,000 per year from the other?
Section 237, Kentucky Constitution, expressly prohibits any such act, and Section 3774, Kentucky Statutes, gives the penalty.
VOTE for DR. H. E. MECHLING FOR CORONER.

NOTICE TO VOTERS
The following section of the Constitution is quoted to show that our present Coroner, Dr. Ellis Duncan, is not eligible for re-election, as it is unlawful for any one to hold a Federal office with salary attached and at the same time serve the county, city or State and receive salary or profit.
Section 237--Constitution:
Offices Incompatible: No member of Congress, or person holding or exercising an office of trust under the United States shall be eligible to hold or exercise any office of trust or profit under this constitution. Recognizing the above law and the fact of Dr. Duncan's ineligibility, I have announced myself as a candidate for the office of Coroner of Jefferson county, subject to the action of the Democratic party at the primary to be held August 4, 1917, and solicit your vote and support.
DR. H. E. MECHLING.

"REGULARS" GUARD POTOMAC BRIDGE
Uncle Sam's regular troops are guarding the railroad bridge which crosses the Potomac river south of Washington. No craft is permitted to approach at night without being hailed, and the decks of all vessels are scanned closely in the daytime. NATHAN KAHN
Nathan Kahn, candidate for re-election as Prosecuting Attorney of the Police Court, subject to the action of the Democratic party, is receiving much encouragement from his fellow-Democrats, who believe that his successful administration deserves an indorsement at the hands of the voters. TAUGHT SALESMANSHIP TO WANAMAKER'S CLERKS
Stanley L. Krebs
"Two Snakes In Eden" is the title Stanley L. Krebs selected for his lecture which will be one of the features on the Chautauqua program here this summer. Dr. Krebs has lectured on business subjects throughout England, France, Russia and Germany. He has addressed some of the largest sales organizations in this country and is the author of standard works on salesmanship and business efficiency. His system of salesmanship was taught in the University of Berlin before the war and is used in the largest schools of business in this country. For three years he was employed by John Wanamaker as a lecturer before his sales force of more than 3,000.

values.caption:
DR. FOLLANSBEE IS DESCENDANT OF GOV. WILLIAM BRADFORD
Dr. L. E. Follansbee, first day lecturer at the Chautauqua, is a direct descendant of Governor William Bradford of the Massachusetts colony, author of the first Thanksgiving proclamation. Dr. Follansbee is a well known Chautauqua lecturer of the "Sunshine' Willits type. In one of his lectures, which he calls "The Puritan and the Cavalier," he used to refer in a brief way to his illustrious ancestor, but says he eliminated all that many years ago, for "it might seem to be said for effect" He has in his possession the original text of the first declaration, a copy of which fell into the hands of a newspaper correspondent last November and was printed throughout the country. This newspaper story brought to light once more the name of Dr. Follansbee in connection with the originator of the American Thanksgiving.

From Shelters in Buildings Destroyed By Boches, French Pour Deadly Fire at
Enemy
The destruction of public building by the Germans in France, while distressing to the residents of villages which have been visited, has not been wholly satisfactory to the invaders. For the French in their recent offensive movements have found in these same ruined buildings some advantageous shelters. Here they have hidden their machine gun batteries and are mowing down the Huns who are opposing them in the open country. The French are fighting like demons at this point "somewhere in France." Their recent drive has been one of the most effective of the war.

STEVE DUNIGAN DEAD.
Many Louisville friends were shocked to hear of the death of Stephen Dunigan, a former Louisville citizen, who for the past several years has been located at Hammond, Ind., where he did a prosperous contracting business. He died Tuesday evening after a short illness and the funeral took place from All Saints' church there Thursday morning. For years Mr. Dunigan was prominent in local political circles, serving as a member of the General Council and as Superintendent of the Street Cleaning Department. After retiring from political life he was in business at Seventh and St. Catherine streets, and had many warm friends in the Dominican parish, who held him in high esteem for his many generous qualities. Besides his wife, Mrs. Margaret Dunigan, and one daughter, Miss Marian Dunigan, he is survived by two sisters, Mrs. Mary Crowe and Mrs. Charles Bent, both of Bridgeport, Conn., and one brother, Joseph Dunigan, who is connected with the local Postal Telegraph Company.

CALLED TO COLORS.
Lieut. John Maloney, until recently a member of the Louisville police force, and under whose leadership and direction the mounted force became the pride of the city and State, has been called into the service of Uncle Sam. Last Friday he received his commission as First Lieutenant in the army, with orders to report at Fort Snelling, Minn. Lieut. Maloney is recognized as a drillmaster of the first class and every inch a soldier--one who will be respected and popular with both his superiors and the men under him and always ready to lead the advance. For years he has been actively identified with the Ancient Order of Hibernians of this city, many of whom are now following the Stars and Stripes. Though Louisville has lost a valuable officer, Uncle Sam has secured an experienced and brave soldier, whom it is hoped will return victorious and with higher commission.

HERE'S THE REAL SHADOW ON HUNLAND
A bigger, blacker and deeper shadow hovers over Germany than the sharp decisive successes of the allied forces from Flanders to Rheims. It is the steel helmeted Yanks on the American front with a foot on German soil and daily being reinforced with what the Hun high command knows now to be "wild-cat fighting men." Yank fighters in a major smash into Germany could break the morale of the homefolks as no other factor could. That's why picked troops are being placed opposite the Yanks. This. is a new picture of our Yank commander, General Pershing, in steel helmet and ready for the word from Foch.

data.caption:
THE SMITHS ARE LEADING
GEORGE SMITH.
The Smiths are again heavily represented in the major leagues as the 1917 pennant races get under way. The Smiths lead the representatives of all other family trees, a distinction which for many years was held by the Joneses. George Smith, who first won fame at Columbia University, Is one of the new players to be added to the New York Giants. In Brooklyn is another pitching Smith, the same being Sherrod Smith, who pitched such sensational ball in the world's series last October. On the same team is Jimmy Smyth, but the difference in spelling keeps him out of the family reunion. Jack Smith and Fred Smith take orders from Miller Huggins, of the Cardinals, and J. Carlyle Smith operates at third base for the Boston Braves. Elmer Smith is one of the regular outfielders of Washington, and "Popboy" Smith is a pitcher for Cleveland.

Marthinus J. Fonnesbeck
Marthinus J. Fonnesbeck was born on his father's farm in Gjeller up, near Herring Denmark, April 20, 1841. As a boy and in early youth he worked as a farm laborer and at the age of eighteen was gaged as a traveling salesman of knitted goods, which occupation he followed until he was 24 years of age, when he was drafted into the Danish Army where he served for two years.
After leaving the army he began business as a wholesale and retail dealer and manufacturer of knitted goods, in Copenhagen, where he worked up a very large business for that time.
In 1892 he closed out his business and set sail for America, and he arrived in Logan with his family in July of that year. Shortly after arriving here he homesteaded a quarter section of dry land near Weston Idaho, on which he located with his family. After a long struggle he succeeded in transforming a desert-like tract of land into a fruitful farm. After ten years he left his farm in charge of two of his sons, and then moved to Logan, where in company with two other sons began the manufacture and sale of knitted goods and established the solid business firm known as the Fonnesbeck Knitting Works.
Mr. Fonnesbeck was a keen student of history and modern politics, and was proud of the fact that he was one of the earliest exponents of the Social Democratic principles in Denmark.
The deceased leaves a wife, four sons, three daughters and twenty-three grand children to mourn his loss.

AMERICAN NAVY ELIMINATES WASTE
JACKIES in the American navy are classed as the best fed body of men in the world. In the ship's galleys every effort is made to eliminate waste.
In the upper photo one of the cooks on the North Dakota is operating a meat slicer that cuts bacon with the least possible wastage. Fat is fuel for fighters. Bacon is badly needed in the allied armies and navies. The allied needs in pork products are 150,000,000 pounds monthly, three times as much as before the war.
Another waste eliminator on the North Dakota is the potato peeler, shown in the lower photo. Nothing is lost except the actual potato skin.
There is a sufficient quantity of potatoes in America for greater use in every home and for all needs of army and navy. Eat more potatoes, eat less wheat.

PHOTOGRAPH OF SURRENDER OF FIRST GERMAN SUBMARINE PRISONERS TO U.S. DESTROYERS
This picture shows the crew of a German U-boat, lined up on the U-boat's deck, surrendering to the United States torpedo boat destroyer Fanning. The destroyer Nicholson aided in the capture.
The men shown in this picture in the act of surrender are the first German submarine prisoners taken by American forces. Receipt of the picture in this country was coincident with the arrival of the first details of the capture.
The submarine's sailors are shown walking down the deck of the submarine to the dory which went over the Fanning, into which the prisoners were transferred. The photo was taken by a member of the American destroyer's crew, and is copyrighted by the Committee on Public Information.

MIDSUMMER FANCIE
Why should we speculate about fashions, past or present? For, after all, from a modish point of view the "have beens" of yesterday and the "may bes" of to-morrow are of but little importance if only the styles of today are of the type to make life interesting, even though war Is raging throughput the land.
And that they most certainly are! So the pessimist who prophesied a dearth of beauty in the realm of summer dress is without honor in his own country, and no one is paying any heed to his calamatous croakings about the direful state of the autumn modes.
For if the poor old calamity howler made a mistake in the one instance he probably would in the other. And make a mistake he assuredly did, for never have clothes been more alluringly attractive than they are at present.
Old Mother Nature believes in just enough variety to make us appreciate her perfections, but in midsummer she is particularly generous and gives to us of her very best. And to show that she appreciates her lavishness the August maid blossoms forth in apparel that matches the weather.
Now is the time for the girl who is a lover of sheer raiment to indulge her fancy. What, for example, is more charming, and incidentally more "comfy," for wear on warm afternoons than a pretty frock of organdie or of voile?
Dead white is trying to certain types, but a creamy tint is universally becoming.
Unusually smart, but at the same time, delightfully simple, is the cream colored dress in which milady of the knitting needles looks so well.
Deep bands of cream filet lace contribute that completesness of conception which always compels admiration, and the frock has attained a degree of ultra-perfection by the addition of a soft satin girdle and loop ends of old rose.
A slipover blouse is a handy little garment to possess, and the one shown here is developed in turquoise blue in a silk and wool weave. Cream wool is employed to edge the novel little affair and also to fashion the corded girdle.
The more summery the day the more charming must be the hat that milady wears.
Fit for any fete is the wide brimmed chapeau cf white Milan, which is lightly veiled in blue Georgette, and carries a wealth of field flowers under a soft cloud of tulle.
Streamers of palest lavender, pink and green in no wise from, but rather do they add to the beauty of the hat.
If we return to the busy knitter for a moment we notice that she has shown equally as good taste In the choice of her chapeau as of her frock.

data.caption:
VICTOR M. HANSEN
From Victor Hansen of the Twenty-eighth Engineers company C now in France comes the following letter to his mother, Mrs. Emma Nelson of 1081 East Seventh street this city: "France, 7-14-'18. "Dear Mother: WE landed here yesterday. I am feeling fine and enjoyed the overseas trip very much. I rather surprised myself. I wasn't seasick at all. At the present we are at a rest camp. We will be here for a few days, then move to our permanent camp some where further inland. Last night I took a good shower bath and cleaned up a bit, so today I am feeling fine. At the present I am, at the Y. M. C. A.
"This morning I went to church and enjoyed the spirit of the meeting very much. "Now dear mother, don't you worry about me. Uncle Sam is taking good care of us. He took all precautions available to land us safely and now it is up to each one to take care of himself.
"We have a splendid captain and he is doing his best to make everything as comfortable as possible for us. The few old men and women I saw yesterday seemed very glad to see us. No young men to be seen; they are all at the front. I will write again when we reach our camp.
"Now dear mother have Bro. Carl write for you and write often, as you know letters from home are a great comfort to a soldier. I will write to the boys and sister, in a few days, as soon as I get a little better acquainted around here.
"Trusting this finds you all well and happy as it leaves me enjoying the best of health and of good cheer. From your loving soldier son, VICTOR. "Address, Am. E. F., 28th Eng. C. C, France."

SCENES WHERE BRITISH ARE DOING THEIR PART IN WAR
British intelligence officers quizzing German prisoners, at left. British trench with sentry posted, at right.
While the major portion of the activity in the allies' great counter offensive has been carried on by the American and French forces the British and Italian troops have been on the alert and have been taking advantage of all opportunities. The quizzing of German prisoners taken during the drive is important. Often times these discouraged soldiers give information of military value. The upper left-hand picture shows British intelligence officers quizzing two prisoners. The taller prisoner is a German and the shorter one a German Pole. The allied men in the trenches must grab what sleep they can while sentries watch for enemy attacks. The other picture shows a sentry at the far end of a British trench keeping his vigil while his comrades enatch a few winks.

values.caption:
CAPTAIN HUSTON
This is the first photograph of Captain Huston, half owner of the New York American league baseball team, as he appears in khaki. It was taken at the camp of the Sixteenth United States engineers, just outside Detroit. The "Cap" assisted in raising the regiment in which he is a commander. As soon as war was declared he dropped every business and social interest and hurriedly got into one of Uncle Sam's uniforms. values.caption:
RUINED RHEIMS STANDS AS BATTERED MONUMENT TO HEROISM OF ALLIED TROOPS FACING HUN FIRE
Ruins of Ecrevisse street in Rheims, at left, and French grenediers fighting as they retreat.
Rheims, a devastated city now, stands as a monument, in a way, to the bravery of the allied troops who fought to hold the German hordes under the terrific fire that laid in ruins cathedrals, churches and homes in Rheims. The remarkable photo at the left shows how completely high explosive shells battered Ecrevisse street in the city. Not a house in the street is undamaged. The photo at the right shows how stubbornly the French grenadiers stopped at each shell hole and evacuated trench and stood off the Germans until forced again to fall back.

Corporal Bibby is survived by his wife and two children who reside in Leigh, England and other relatives some of whom live in the United States. White bread, a luxury unknown to the French for a long time, is served to him daily. Thousands of loaves are baked and thousands of sacks of flour are consumed in supplying his daily needs. All the flour transported from the United States as well as most of the other foodstuffs he uses. Enlisted men detailed to the field bakeries which accompany the army look after Sammy's wants as far as the staff of life is concerned. values.caption:
Hindenburg Thrust Nears Amiens
(Showing Changes Up to 4 o'clock This Afternoon)
Amiens, which marked the high tide of the German invasion in 1914, is apparently the great objective of the new German drive. It is an important railroad center, only eighteen miles from Albert, west of which the British are now fighting, on the Somme River. It is eighty-four miles north of Paris and forty-five miles from the English Channel, marking the nearest approach to the coast in the present thrust. The heavy black line marks the present position of the British forces. The double line shows where the French are fighting. Yesterday's front is indicated by the dotted line.

PARIS REFUGEES FROM FOE'S MONSTER GUN SEEK CELLARS AND DON'T LET IT WORRY 'EM

data.caption:
LIEUT. J. F. SNEDAKER
Second Lieut. John F. Snedaker, son of Mr. and Mrs. J. F. Snedaker has been visiting in this city on a furlough from the Presidio, San Francisco, where he has been attending the officers' training school for some time. Lieutenant Snedaker left Ogden on Thursday for Camp Taylor, Kentucky.
The young man has a host of friends in this city where he attended and graduated from the Weber Normal college. The first of last year he attended the Leland Stanford university of California and the latter part of the year was spent in study at the University of Utah.
Lieutenant Snedaker successfully passed the examinations at the officers training school at the Presidio and was commissioned a second lieutenant on September 16, and ordered to go to Camp Zachary Taylor, Kentucky.

data.caption:
FRANCE'S HERO
GENERAL GOURAUD
Gen. Gouraud is the man who stopped the Germans between Rheims and Massiges last week. Withdrawing his troops when the German attack commenced, he waited for them to get past his old front line and then let loose a terrific fire which ended the drive. Gouraud led the French army at the Dardanelles in 1915. Like Gen. Pau, he has but one arm, but this only makes him dearer to French hearts.

data.caption:
IRVING GOSNELL IS LAID TO REST IN CITY CEMETERY
Irving Gosnell, aged 20 years and a splendid young Ogdenite, passed away Thursday at 7:45 p. m. of pneumonia, following an attack of Spanish influenza of one week's duration.
The young man was an employe of the Ogden Steam Laundry and the son of Mr. and Mrs. James Gosnell of 2550 Van Buren avenue.
Funeral services were held yesterday at 1 p. m. in the Ogden City cemetery, Rev. C. H. Garver and Elder Burdett being the speakers. Mrs. Mary Farley gave the vocal selections.
Young Mr. Gosnell was very well known in Ogden and well liked by his employers. Besides his parents, three brothers and one sister, survive, one brother being at present in Galveston, Texas, with the Marines.

data.caption:
NOW IT SEEMS THAT UKRAINE-GERMAN PEACE PACT MAX BE ANOTHER SORT OF "SCRAP OF PAPER".
The signing of the Ukraine-German peace pact. The photo shows Count Czernin. Austria (1); von Kuhlmann, Germany (2); Radoslavoff, Bulgaria (3); Talaat Pasha, Turkey (4); General Hoffman, Germany (5), and one of the Ukrainian delegates (6).
It now appears that the treaty of peace signed between Germany and the Ukraine state is not likely to endure. The Ukrainian Rada, though it made the treaty, is losing control and may not be able to give Germany the promised aid. The Ukrainian socialists have aided the Russian Bolsheviki army in recapturing Odessa and throughout the Ukraine the people have resisted the Teuton efforts to get foodstuffs.

British Grain Ship Destroyed in Great Fire Along Waterfront of Baltimore,
Incendiary plotters are believed to have caused the $5,000,000 fire which swept part of the water front at Baltimore recently and destroyed the steamship Kerry Range, laden with grain for the British Government. The blaze was probably the most spectacular that has been seen in the Maryland port in years. The fire spread quickly along the docks and the Kerry Range, moored between two of the blazing piers, was fairly enveloped before she was released and drawn into midstream by fire boats. The picture shows her ablaze, with the smoke of the fire darkening the skies. The chief gunner was killed on board and many are missing.

data.caption:
Russian Women Harvest Wheat for the Armies.
Russian women are fighting in the harvest field as well as in the trenches--bringing in the sheaves as well as German prisoners. The picture shows that, despite unsettled political and economic conditions, the new republic is assured an ample winter food supply. These peasant women, working on a threshing machine in South Russia, have paid no heed to
the German propaganda.

values.caption:
Taking Woman Wounded By Bosche to Hospital
Stretcher bearers are taking this woman, wounded behind the Canadian lines by Boche bombardment, to a dressing station in order that her wounds may be cared for. Sights like this are common behind the front. Thousands of women have been wounded by the Germans during the war, and many emergency hospitals have been established behind the allies' lines for their care until their recovery.

data.caption:
Says British Soon Will Be Bombing in Reprisal
Sir Auckland Geddes, British minister of national service, in a speech delivered at Nottingham said that the grim work of bombing German towns and villages would be in full swing “before many moons had elapsed." He said he wished it had been possible to avoid inflicting that last punishment on women and innocent children in Germany, but that the brutal spirit ruling Germany made it inevitable.

DEATH OF A. O. NORCROSS.
Lifelong Resident of West Dummerston
Father of Four Residents of This
Town--Funeral Today.
Alonzo Orrison Norcross, 81, of West Dummerston, died Wednesday morning at 2 in his home, after an illness of two months with a heart trouble. During that time he had been able to be about and was not confined to the bed. Ho leaves besides his wife, five children, Frank A. Norcross, Mrs. L. F. McCrellis and Herbert S. Norcross, all of Brattleboro, Mrs. Henry O. Halladay of West Brattleboro, and Mrs. J. W. Wood of Rochester, N. Y. A daughter, Mary S., wife of Harry Horton of Kalamazoo, died in 1906. He also leaves

TWO AUTOS "SCRAPPED" IN FATAL DOWNTOWN CRASH
One dead, two probably fatally hurt and three others injured is the casualty toll resulting from a right-angle collision between two automobiles at Eighth and South streets this morning. The heavy machine shown in the photograph, running north on Eighth street, was hurled 100 feet and was lashed to scrap-iron against the wall of a music store when struck by a Ford running east on South street. The driver of the Ford, Harry Schwartz, was killed instantly. The machine was wrecked.

SALVAGING CARLOADS OF FOOD FROM DELAWARE RIVER
Heroic measures were adopted this morning in raising four carloads of fish, meat and merchandise from the bottom of the Delaware River. The cars slipped into the water yesterday from a lighter of the Pennsylvania Railroad just off the Federal street wharf, Camden. This unusual photograph shows one of the cars just being raised above the surface of the river by a giant crane worked from a mammoth barge.

data.caption:
I have not made any threats. Neither have I made any promises. It is not my intention to turn faithful and efficient servants of the public out of office if elected Mayor. I am after efficiency and any man now holding public office who has proved his efficiency will be retained in office. My opponents have said that my motto is: "To the victor belongs the spoils." My motto is that the spoils belong to the people and these spoils are economical government, and permanent improvements produced by efficient officials.
J. C. COHEN,
Our Next Mayor

NEW MAXWELL MODEL HERE
WHILE the Maxwell factory has made but few changes in the new Maxwell, these changes are important and are in the nature of real improvements. The new cars have Atwater-Kent ignition instead of the old magneto, this being in line with the changes made by the builders of higher priced cars. There are some minor changes in the interior finish while the instrument board is more complete than in the old models. Another change, and an important one. is the extra wheel, carried on a bracket at the rear. In most cars, only an extra rim is supplied. The illustration shows the Buquor brothers with the district representatives of the Maxwell in one of the new cars.

Dobrudja, Germany has awarded to Bulgaria.

data.caption:
FIREMEN NAB GIRL FROM'RISKY PERCH
Lona Beer, an escaped inmate from the Sleighton Farms, gave a number of policemen and firemen some anxious moments last night until they took her from a perilous position on a narrow ledge that extends around the Reading Terminal, to which she had fled when discovered at the station. When policemen sought to approach her along the ledge she threatened to jump. Then firemen with a ladder were called and again Lona said she would leap if any attempt were made to approach her. Finally when the firemen had spread a net below her she allowed herself to be taken struggling from her dangerous perch.

HE DENIES WHEAT YARN OF GERMANS
F. Quattrone.
F. Quattrone, Italian high commissioner to the United States, denies positively the statement that wheat shipped from this country to Italy for war use comes back to this country as spaghetti. He also protests the statements that ships available for ocean use are lying idle in Italian ports. Both of these charges, Quattrone and other officials believe, are Hun propoganda. Quattrone says that further reduction of tonnage in the U. S.-Italy trade would menace Italy and its army with starvation.

IMMIGRANT CHINEE BUILDS RAILROAD
Chin Gee Hee.
Thirty years ago when Chin Gee Hee came to American, an immigrant, he had an ambition to build a railroad in his native China. He started business in Seattle with his savings and after prospering returned to China, interesting capital in his project and directing the construction of the road. Graveyards are so many in China that Chin Gee Hee's chief difficulty was in overcoming his countrymen's opposition to a railroad that would necessarily pass through many of the burial grounds.

They represent the rank of full general, and the men are three of the only seven Americans who have won the title, the other four being Washington, Grant, Sherman and Sheridan. This is the first time in America's history that the nation has had three full generals at one time.

Britain Admits Error in Ceding Helgoland to Germany
View of Helgoland and map showing its relation to Germany.
The British government now admits that it made a tremendous blunder when it ceded the island of Helgoland to Germany in 1890. This island in the North sea, twenty-eight miles from the German mainland, is as impregnable as the Rock of Gibraltar. It controls the approaches to Wilhelmshaven, the German naval base, and to the Kiel canal, which connects the Elbe and the Baltic sea, and enables Germany to shift her fleet at will from the North to the Baltic sea.

data.caption:
THE PEOPLE IN THE STORY
JERRY ARCHER, who, with his elder brother Paul, is actively continuing the business of the Archer Tool Works, is clubbed into unconsciousness and arrested by Patrolman Strongburger when the young man, outraged at the policeman's brutal treatment of Mortiz Rosenscweig, comes to that prisoner's assistance. Rosenscweig has been taken into custody as the final step in the petty persecution arising from factional differences in the "Bloody Fifth" Ward. Jerry is released from jail, his case is dropped and Strongburger "broke" - that is, requested to resign before being "fired" - as the result of the intervention of a family friend.
WILLARD H. BUCKINGHAM, financial genius and the most powerful man in Philadelphia. At his nod political bosses as well as the underlings, move and, and move fast. When Buckingham's daughter,
RUTH BUCKINGHAM, tells her father that Jerry is missing, the great man calls EDMUNDS an "unofficial official," on the long-distance telephone at Atlantic City. Jerry's release is due to the effective work of Edmonds, Buckingham's "push button." From
MICHAEL KELLY, a Carey division leader, Jerry, while resting in the Lafayette Club before returning home, gets his first lesson in practical politics. He learns that the "Organization's" primary object is "dealin' out jobs" and that just so long as it performs its part of the pact with big business and turns over Republican majorities in all legislative and national elections it will not be interfered with locally.
SYLVY AURESTSKY, a beautiful young Jewish girl, stops Jerry on the street as he is about to leave the club for his home and thanks him for his manly defense of the persecuted Rosensweig. When she leaves him, Jerry notices a sinister figure following the girl. Kelly informs him that the person is
JOE MALDONO, a thug, pickpocket and gunman. As Sylvy is about to enter her home the Fifth Ward gangster stops her. When she refuses his invitation to attend a dance he threatens her and is about to employ force when Sylvy's father intervenes mildly. Maldono, piqued and revengeful, has Aurentsky arrested on the charge of receiving stolen goods. While this is going on Jerry and Ruth, safe in their Overbrook homes, have formed a "Save-Philidelphia" party with the watchword, "For Sylvy Aurentsky." In a discussion with his father and brother just before this Jerry learns that
JIM RAND, a Councils' lobbyist, has demanded $3000 to put a franchise for a spur track across Howard street through the municipal legislative body in forty-eight hours. For weeks Councils have refused to act upon the Archer's application, and Government is seriously tied up.

American Troops Drive Germans Across Marne
General Foch has thrown American reserves into the great Second Battle of the Marne.
United States troops on Tuesday attacked a German force which crossed the Marne south of Jaulgonne (indicated by the arrow on the map), and after a short but fierce fight threw them back across the stream and destroyed the bridges.
It was the first time the Germans had attempted to force a crossing of the famous river since the start of their drive, and America is to be congratulated that it was her own soldiers who frustrated the enemy.
The Americans captured 100 prisoners in the battle. They are also taking part In the Marne battle at Neuilly Wood, according to the announcement of the French War Office.

PAGE MR. BRYAN! THESE SOLDIERS ARE ALL GOING TO BE "TANKED UP"
When they couldn't find an ordinary home on the western front these Tommies just went and got "tanked up" for the night. As you'll see by the picture, there was nothing reprehensible about it no need to call Mr. Bryan or the head of the W. C. T. U. Billets for soldiers cannot be chosen as one chooses when house hunting. And when the officers of these Tommies found this huge concrete tank, bowled over during a bombardment, they seized upon it with glee and dispatch and made of it a cozy home for a score of tired fighters. The Tommies didn't kick at all on the "outside stairway" and one of the things they particularly liked about it was --paradox-- it was dry.

data.caption:
Irene Bordoni DESCRIBES HER BEST AFTERNOON GOWN
(Written for the Ogden Standard by Irene Bordoni, "best dressed woman on the stage.")
This street costume, which I use for dress occasions in the afternoon, is in the French style. The skirt consists of four panels starting only at the hip and exposing the white chiffon foundation up to the waist line at the sides, as well as at the spaces between the green panels. The crush girdle is of the same green satin, as is also the small pointed bib-effect which emerges just above the girdle. The blouse is made of white chiffon matching the foundation of the skirt and is simply made with a deep laydown collar. There are leg-o'-mutton sleeves with deep cuffs, which are finished off by white chiffon frills, drooping over the hand.
There are three ornaments fashioned of green and white beads which adorn the vest. The two small ornaments are suspended by a triangular shaped piece from the lower edges of the bib, while the larger ornament hangs directly from the left side of the girdle and is finished off with ropes of beads. The costume is completed by a white long-handled parasol and a large sailor hat of broad-brim variety which is made of green satin-faced with double folds of white chiffon. There is a somewhat unique ornament on the hat in the shape of a key which pierces the crown. I call this my "French Key to Victory!" I wear with this costume white shoes and stockings.
This is my favorite afternoon gown because of the color, green, which in French is the color for "hope," and because the costume is very plain while at the same time highly decorative.

THE FATE OF LITTLE JACK IS QUESTION IN DE SAULLES CASE
Here's Blanca De Saulles, defendant in the murder case now on trial at Mineola, L. I.; with little Jack, her fatherless son for whom she shot her faithless husband, and surrounding her face an artist's sketch-chart of her troubled life. The story opens with Jack De Saulles (1), Yale football star, who met her while traveling (2) in her South American native land, and made her (3) his bride. After the birth of (4) their son, the ex-football star returned to the gay lights (5) of Broadway, until finally the Chilean beauty got a divorce (6). Deprived of her son part of the time, the mother (7) shot and killed De Saulles, and is (8) now on trial for life and liberty. This brings us to the most serious question now: What will become of Jack?

Mrs. Margaret Arbon of 3005 Washington avenue has received a postal card photo of her son, Leland Arbon, from Camp Dodge, Iowa. The picture is a remarkable one, Mr. Arbon appearing five times in the one picture. On the back he writes that Thanksgiving dinner at the fort was a sumptuous one and that the boys are certainly being well treated by Uncle Sam. "While I have seen some fine, big cities," he writes, "there Is nothing so fine to me as dear old Utah."

Women Show Way to Kitchen Economics
Women prominent in society are touring the United States in what they have named the "Conservation Special" in an effort to curtail or eliminate waste in food production. They are also giving practical demonstrations of preserving processes and household economics. That the movement is a very popular one is shown by the crowds of women who gather around the special train at each stop and in their eagerness to gather information as to household economics. The theme of the demonstrations is that by modern scientific methods much food that was previously allowed to rot may be utilized by care and economy. The baggage car of this special train contains jars, cans and dehydrators and other equipment for demonstration work. A pamphlet entitled "Hints to Housewives" is scattered at every stopping place. The photographs herewith show the yonng women of the Food Conservation Battalion giving practical demonstrations in the preparation and conservation of foodstuffs.

SUDDEN DEATH OF Dr. C.K. M'MURDY.
Dr. C.K. McMurdy, formerly of Ogden, died suddenly last Monday in Stamford, New York, according to a message received today by Clyde Fulton of the Fulton Pharmacy. Dr. McMurdy was formerly a well-known physician of this city and a very prominent and active member of Odgen lodge, No. 719. B.P.O. Elks. He will be remembered as a participant in several club activities given, while he resided here. Mr. McMurdy married Miss Rita Lewis, a Salt Lake girl, while in Ogden. No details regarding his death have been received. The funeral will be held Saturday.

STRIKING MIDINETTES OF PARIS BESIEGE CHAMBER OF DEPUTIES
Striking midinettes outside chamber of deputies, Paris.
Parisian midinettes, with women working in allied trades, recently called a general strike. Fifteen thousand of them, discontented with their wages, walked out. They stormed the chamber of deputies and a petite midinette, raised above tho crowd by a soldier, told a committee of deputies what the strikers wanted.

WOMEN LINE UP TO BUY MILK FOR BABIES IN PETROGRAD STREETS
Typical line outside Petrograd milk depot.
Necessities of life are scarce in Russia and what there is is so loosely handled that suffering is great in the poorer quarters. Lines like the one in the picture may be seen in front of almost any store in Petrograd. These women are waiting for a chance to buy milk for their babies. The government has been in such chaotic state that the method of distribution has been left to the dealers almost entirely.

EVERS, PEPPER BOX OF CUBS AND BRAVES, MAY NEVER PLAY BASEBALL AGAIN
The unconditional release of Johnny Evers by the Phillies may not mean his retirement from baseball-it may be that the 1918 season will again see him in uniform, either as manager of one of the few clubs which will require new pilots or as adviser to the manager of some other club in a capacity similar to that he held with Pat Moran. But it is not likely that Johnny will ever actively take the field again. His age and his physical condition are both arguments against this. Few second basemen have surpassed Evers' record at the keystone sack over a long period of years.

Hon Wm B. Wilson

TIGER GRIDIRON STAR LAST FALL NOW OFFICER IN REGULAR ARMY
Eddie Driggs.
Eddie Driggs, who starred as a halfback on the 1915 and 1916 Princeton teams is now a second lieutenant in the regular army and may soon see service in France. Driggs was granted a first lieutenant's commission in the engineers reserve corps some months ago, but when orders to join the colors were forthcoming he enlisted in the regular army. When Driggs was given the choice of a first lieutenancy without active service and a second lieutenant's commission in the regular army he didn't take long to decide that he preferred the latter.

Chautauquas to Hear Exposition Band
Thaviu's Great Organization Which Opened and Closed San Francisco Exposition Coming on Fifth Day of Chautauqua
Thaviu's Band Is coming to Chautauqua—thirty selected musicians from the great musical organization which both opened and closed the San Francisco Exposition and led by the magnetic Thaviu himself. Of the sixteen bands of nation-wide reputation which entertained the great crowds during the Exposition season, Thaviu's was the only one requested for a return engagement. They had so successfully pleased the throngs during the opening days that the directors commissioned their return for the closing weeks.
The secret of Thaviu's popularity is not expressed so much in the size of his organization as in the unusual personnel and the fact that Thaviu is a master director of his accomplished musicians. All band music critics comment upon the sparkle, life and dashing brilliancy of his musical interpretation.
Two full concerts will be given on the fifth day of Chautauqua. In addition to the band in the evening, three grand opera singers from Thaviu's own grand opera organization will appear as soloists.

ANNETTE FORD AND THE FASHION GIRLS IN A SCENE FROM THE MUSICAL COMEDY, "THE PRINCESS PAT," NEW YEAR'S
"The Princess Pat." Henry Blossom and Victor Herbert's latest comic opera, which reigned Queen of Broadway for many months, comes to the Orpheum Theater on New Year's Day, January 1, for a matinee and evening performance only. It is one of those very, very rare comic operas which are at once comic and operatic. The book and lyrics are in Mr. Blossom's best vein, with pith and point to the comedy, while Mr. Herbert's music not only excels the best that the put into "Mlle. Modiste," "The Red Mill," and "The Prima Donna," but in one or two of the concerted numbers approached closely the distinction of his grand opera efforts in "Natoma" and "Madeleine." Add to these facts the introduction of principals and ensemble that can sing as well as look beautiful and we have the reason for the success of "The Princess Pat."

When the Lutzow Went Down
The true story of the Battle of Jutland, claimed by both the English and the Germans as a victory, is printed in the English language here for the first time. P. Krug, one of the Lutzow survivors, prepared a pamphlet, which was printed at The Hague in Dutch, telling his experiences on board Admiral Hipper's flagship before it went down a victim to British marksmanship. So vivid are the recollections of the frightful scenes during the battle that the author lives through the harrowing details again; he seems to be fighting the battle over once more. This booklet has never been printed in the German language. The Evening Ledger has secured by cable the exclusive rights to this pamphlet in the United States and Canada.

AFTER ALL MAYBE FISH WILL WIN WAR; AT ANY RATE BIG DRIVE ON FINNY TRIBE IS BEING LAUNCHED
Above - Whalers on Atlantic coast. Below - First of fleet of steam trawlers ready for launching to help Hoover.
Now comes the cry from the food administration: "Fish may win the war." And the photos show that if the fish are to be a factor they will be a power on the side of the allies. In one photo Atlantic coast fishermen are busily cutting up whale carcasses for food. In the other is shown, ready for launching, a big steam trawler of the Eastern Fisheries Company, the first of a fleet of ten trawlers being built to bring in three million pounds of fish a week. The company has put $10,000,000 into the project and hopes to be a great aid to Hoover in the conservation of beef and pork.

This remarkable news picture or the Yanks' offensive northwest of Verdun is the first to be received in this country.
